title: For Sale:  Walther PPS 9mm, like new
postcontent:
Used Walther PPS 9mm, has fired between 150-250 rds.  This pistol makes an excellent carry weapon, as it is flat and lightweight without compromising the accuracy of a longer barrel or the comfort of a larger grip.

The Walther PPS is a short recoil-operated locked breech semi-automatic pistol that uses a modified Browning cam-lock system adapted from the Hi-Power pistol. The PPS has a glassfiber-reinforced polymer frame and steel slide assembly. It can be broken down into its main parts or field stripped with a take down catch without the help of tools.
The PPS features three safeties (trigger safety, internal firing pin safety and QuickSafe feature) of which the external integrated trigger safety inner lever mechanism contained within the trigger serves as an additional passive drop safety. The pistol has a loaded chamber indicator in the form of a witness opening at the top of the slide/ejection port. By looking into this opening the user can see if a cartridge is present in the chamber.

Features include:
Low profile three dot combat sights - won't snag on clothing

title: For Sale:  7.62x25 Ammo - 1050 Rounds Brass Case Polish Military
postcontent:
With over 38 years of collecting old military firearms behind me I've had more CZ52's and TOK pistols than you can shake a stick at. Plus I've had a couple of PPSH's as well. So I've shot up a ton of 7.62x25 ammo over the years and my personal favorite by has always been the Polish surplus stuff that I have listed here.   

It's brass case with a Full Metal Jacket bullet. The jacket material is actually a two part deal with a thick steel inner jacket covered by a thinner copper outer jacket, and that's why this ammo attracts a magnet. It's probably also a part of why this stuff penetrates like crazy. The truth is that this round's penetration ability comes from a combination of very high velocity coupled with a small diameter bullet that has a thick steel inner jacket. There really isn't anything quite like the 7.62x25 in our American pistol cartridge lineup.    

This Polish ammo also always seemed to shoot a little cleaner than other surplus and it's sure to fire. Make no mistake it is corrosive primed so cleaning your firearm is a must and you'll have no problems if you simply clean your gun after shooting this ammo or any other corrosive surplus.   

Then the last thing is that this ammo is noticeably hotter than any other surplus or commercial ammo I've tried. This may be due to the fact that much of this ammo was used by the Poles for their sub-machine guns. If you shoot it side by side with anything else I think you'll notice the difference too. I've shot this same ammo in a number of CZ52's and various TOK pistols without issue, however all of my firearms were in tip top condition. So you must be sure your firearms are in top shape too before firing this ammo or any other military grade ammo in them. When in doubt seek the advice of a professional gunsmith.   

THIS LISTING IS FOR 15 SEALED 70 ROUND BOXES FOR A TOTAL OF 1050 ROUNDS. THE LOOSE ROUNDS SHOWN ARE FROM AN OPEN BOX AND ARE NOT INCLUDED IN THIS LISTING.   

Price is $350 which works out to $.33 per round. Pickup locally in the Brandon area or I would consider shipping at buyers expense to places where this ammo is legal to ship to.

title: For Sale:  Response--beware-of-sks-scam--kreg-is-a-scammer
postcontent:
This is a response to the uneducated idiot that thinks he knows about Sks's. The SKS that this ignorant punk is talking about is a all numbers matching Yugo SKS. These rifles were refurbished by the country of origin. This one by Yugoslavia. The Russians and the Chinese did the same thing just a little different. The Yugos usually had a electric pencil serial number that they used to scribe in the serial number when all the parts were put back together during refurbishing. It is what it is called forced matched. The Russians xxxxx out The original number and put the new one during this process. This was done 40 or 50 years ago by the arsenal not me you idiot. I'm glad you did not buy this gun because you are too stupid to own a gun and might hurt somebody or yourself. 
I have sold quite a few guns and you are the only one that his come up with this ridiculous theory of counterfeiting or stealing SKS parts.I have owned well over 100 SKS's in the past 25 years and still have quite a few. I have been collecting for a long time.I sold a Izzy Russian SKS for $1000 and the guy that bought it was completely aware that it was a refurbished gun. The numbers were xxxx out with the newer numbers just below it. If you are looking for a non-refurbished SKS with all matching serial numbers you will be paying much more. I have one Russian that is like that. All the rest of my SKS'S are probably refurbished just like the one that you are bitching about.
Like I said I have sold quite a few guns. I have a few guys that have bought up to 4 SKS'S off of me and are very happy. They were bought legal sold legal and were not altered by me like you claim. Do some research next time before you look and sound like a complete idiot on this subject.
I was wearing a sweatshirt with a hood that day that you met me because it was about 32° and windy not because I am "shady. We did not meet in the middle of nowhere either it was about 100 feet from interstate five at a gas station. This would not even be an issue if you did not start texting me threatening me and making false accusations.
The 2nd pic is of the actual gun in question and is a perfect example. See the serial numbers and compare with the pics he put up.
The 3rd pic is an example of a Russian sks and also not done by me.
The 1rst picture is an example of another subject that he knows nothing about but was done by me. LOL

title: For Sale:  Military Collector - very good condition VZ-52
location: Desoto County, North West Mississippi, Mississippi
postcontent:
The VZ-52 rifle is a self-loading rifle developed shortly after the Second World War in Czechoslovakia chambered in 7.62x45mm.  (I have the adapter kit for 7.62x39)

It is a shoulder-fired semi-automatic rifle with a tilting-bolt locking mechanism powered by an annular short-stroke gas piston system. The bolt is locked by two lugs that recess into slots machined into the receiver. However, unlike most vertically-locking breech mechanism, the rifle's bolt has the unusual feature of tipping the bolt frontally to lock the mechanism, whereas other tipping bolt designs tip the bolt to the rear.[1] The piston is actuated by residual gases from the bore, vented into a sleeve surrounding the barrel to overcome the inertia of the bolt carrier, bolt and the resistance of the return spring in order to unlock the chamber, eject the empty cartridge casing and then introduce a new round into the chamber upon return to battery.

The barrel is press-fit and pinned into the receiver. The manual safety switch is placed inside of the trigger guard and is manipulated by the shooter's index finger. The trigger mechanism closely resembles that used in the American M1 Garand semi-automatic rifle. The cocking handle is integrated into the bolt carrier and is located on the right side of the rifle; this arrangement enables the shooter to reload the rifle without disturbing his aim.

The rifle is equipped with open-type iron sights with a hooded front post and V-notch rear sight placed on a sliding tangent, adjustable for elevation between 100–950 m. The rifle can also accept day and night-time optics that interface with an optional, receiver-mounted side rail. The one-piece pistol grip stock is carved from either walnut or beech and stained a yellowish-brown color; the stock has a hollowed butt which is used as a storage compartment for a cleaning rod, oil bottle and accessories. The rifle has an integral blade bayonet which folds into a recess carved into the stock on the right side.

The vz. 52 feeds from a detachable box magazine with a 10-round cartridge capacity but could also be rapidly recharged from stripper clips with the bolt retracted. For this purpose, a stripper clip guide is milled into the front face of the bolt carrier, aligning with the magazine when the bolt is locked in the open position. This is the primary method of reloading the rifle as infantrymen were only issued 2 magazines per rifle. It ejects cartridge cases vigorously forward and to the left.

If these holsters were dirty or well worn I wouldn't sell them. These hybrids offer the most in concealability/function and offer alot of adjustment by raising or lowering the belt clips.
